Creating a simple image carousel component using React.js and Tailwind CSS can be done in a few steps. First, make sure you have React and Tailwind CSS properly installed and imported in your project. Then, we'll create a basic React component that includes the carousel functionality. Follow these steps:

1. Install the required packages for React and Tailwind CSS. You can use the Create React App for simplified setup. This will already have Tailwind CSS configured. 

    Run these commands in your terminal:

    ```bash
    npx create-react-app my-app --template=typescript  // Set up a new React project
    cd my-app
    npm install tailwindcss@latest postcss@latest autoprefixer@latest -D  // Install Tailwind CSS and related packages
    npx tailwindcss init -p
    ```

   After running these commands, make sure to update the `tailwind.config.js` file like this:

   ```javascript
   const defaultTheme = require('tailwindcss/defaultTheme');

   module.exports = {
     content: [
       "./src/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}",
     ],
     theme: {
       extend: {
         fontFamily: {
           sans: ['Inter var', ...defaultTheme.fontFamily.sans],
         },
       },
     },
     plugins: [],
   }
   ```

   This will give Tailwind access to your JavaScript and TypeScript code.

2. Create a new file for your carousel component, for example: `ImageCarousel.jsx` and add the following code:

   ```jsx
   import React, { useState } from 'react';

   const images = [
     '/image1.jpg',
     '/image2.jpg',
     '/image3.jpg',
     '/image4.jpg',
     '/image5.jpg',
   ];

   const ImageCarousel = () => {
     const [currentIndex, setCurrentIndex] = useState(0);

     const goToPrevSlide = () => {
       const isFirstSlide = currentIndex === 0;
       const newIndex = isFirstSlide ? images.length - 1 : currentIndex - 1;
       setCurrentIndex(newIndex);
     };

     const goToNextSlide = () => {
       const isLastSlide = currentIndex === images.length - 1;
       const newIndex = isLastSlide ? 0 : currentIndex + 1;
       setCurrentIndex(newIndex);
     };

     return (
       <div className="relative w-full h-96 bg-gray-200">
         <img
           src={images[currentIndex]}
           alt="carousel-image"
           className="w-full h-full object-cover"
         />
         <button
           onClick={goToPrevSlide}
           className="absolute top-1/2 left-4 bg-white hover:bg-gray-100 text-black font-bold py-2 px-4 rounded"
           style={{ transform: 'translateY(-50%)' }}
         >
           Prev
         </button>
         <button
           onClick={goToNextSlide}
           className="absolute top-1/2 right-4 bg-white hover:bg-gray-100 text-black font-bold py-2 px-4 rounded"
           style={{ transform: 'translateY(-50%)' }}
         >
           Next
         </button>
       </div>
     );
   };

   export default ImageCarousel;
   ```

   This component uses a `currentIndex` state to display the current image, and the two functions `goToPrevSlide` and `goToNextSlide` are used to update the `currentIndex` when the user clicks on the prev/next buttons.

3. In your main `App` component, import and render the `ImageCarousel` component like this:

   ```jsx
   import React from 'react';
   import ImageCarousel from './ImageCarousel';

   const App = () => {
     return (
       <div className="App">
         <ImageCarousel />
       </div>
     );
   };

   export default App;
   ```

4. Now, you can start your React application using the command `npm start`. The image carousel should be rendered in your app.

Remember to use your own image URLs and adjust the CSS classes if needed. You can also use other carousel packages like `react-slick` for more advanced functionalities, but this simple example should give you a basic idea of how to create a React image carousel component using Tailwind CSS.

