Here is my optimized solution in C#:

```csharp
using System;

public class FibonacciService
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Calculates the next 20 Fibonacci numbers that exceed the given threshold.
    /// </summary>
    /// <param name="threshold">The threshold value for Fibonacci numbers.</param>
    /// <returns>The next 20 Fibonacci numbers that exceed the given threshold.</returns>
    public long[] GetFibonacciNumbersAboveThreshold(int threshold)
    {
        if (threshold < 0)
        {
            throw new ArgumentException("Threshold must be non-negative.");
        }

        long[] fibNumbers = new long[20];
        long num1 = 1, num2 = 1, index = 0;

        while (num2 <= threshold)
        {
            long temp = num2;
            num2 += num1;
            num1 = temp;
        }

        fibNumbers[index++] = num2;

        while (index < 20)
        {
            long temp = num2;
            num2 += num1;
            num1 = temp;

            fibNumbers[index++] = num2;
        }

        return fibNumbers;
    }
}

public class Program
{
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        FibonacciService fibonacciService = new FibonacciService();
        int threshold = 20;

        try
        {
            long[] fibNumbers = fibonacciService.GetFibonacciNumbersAboveThreshold(threshold);

            Console.WriteLine($"The next 20 fibonacci numbers above {threshold} are:");

            foreach (long num in fibNumbers)
            {
                Console.WriteLine(num);
            }
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Error: {ex.Message}");
        }
    }
}
```

This solution provides a method `GetFibonacciNumbersAboveThreshold(int threshold)` in the `FibonacciService` class to calculate the next 20 Fibonacci numbers above the given threshold value. The `FibonacciService` class is designed for encapsulation and separation of concerns.

In the `Main` method, the `FibonacciService` instance is used to call the `GetFibonacciNumbersAboveThreshold(int threshold)` method, and the results are printed to the console. The solution also uses exception handling to address possible runtime errors.

Regarding performance analysis, the time complexity of the Fibonacci numbers generation is O(1) because it only involves a fixed number of operations, and the space complexity is O(1) as well, as it uses a fixed-size array to store the Fibonacci numbers. The threshold checking and Fibonacci numbers looping are both O(N) with a constant factor applied to the threshold value.

