def search_in_rotated_array(nums, target):
    left, right = 0, len(nums) - 1

    while left <= right:
        mid = left + (right - left) // 2
        if nums[mid] == target:
            return mid

        if nums[mid] >= nums[left]:
            if target >= nums[left] and target < nums[mid]:
                right = mid - 1
            else:
                left = mid + 1
        else:
            if target > nums[mid] and target <= nums[right]:
                left = mid + 1
            else:
                right = mid - 1
    return -1

Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) node pools operations like scaling or listing for a specific project ID are not directly managed by Kubernetes API. Instead, they are managed by Google Cloud APIs.

Unfortunately, at this time, the Kubernetes Java Client library doesn't support GKE-specific features like managing node pools as they are outside the scope of the base Kubernetes API.

To perform these operations, you'll need to use the Google Cloud Java Client Libraries instead, which have support for many services in Google Cloud Platform, including Google Kubernetes Engine.

Here's an example of how you might list node pools using Google Cloud Libraries in a Java application:

```java
String projectID = "my-project-id";
String zone = "us-central1-a";
String clusterID = "my-cluster-id";

try {
    // Create the GKE client
    NodePoolsSettings nodePoolsSettings = NodePoolsSettings.newBuilder().build();
    NodePoolsClient nodePoolsClient = NodePoolsClient.create(nodePoolsSettings);

    // Prepare the request
    String parent = String.format("projects/%s/locations/%s/clusters/%s",
                            projectID, zone, clusterID);
    ListNodePoolsRequest request = ListNodePoolsRequest.newBuilder()
                            .setParent(parent)
                            .build();

    // Send the request
    for (NodePool np : nodePoolsClient.listNodePools(request).iterateAll()) {
        System.out.println(np.getName());
    }
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
}
```
Please replace `"my-project-id"`, `"us-central1-a"` and `"my-cluster-id"` with your actual Project ID, Zone, and Cluster ID respectively.

Remember that using the Google Cloud Client Libraries requires authentication. If your application running on a Google Cloud environment that has default credentials like GCE, GAE, GKE, or Cloud Functions, it uses these credentials by default. If you're developing locally or on another platform, you have to manually provide service account credentials.

Make sure to add the following Maven dependency to use Google Cloud Libraries in your project:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.google.cloud</groupId>
    <artifactId>google-cloud-container</artifactId>
    <version>1.1.2</version>
</dependency>
```

Please ensure to use the latest version suitable for your project.

